[35:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'description below. Next up, we have a pretty cool 3D model generator. It\'s called vertex regen and this generates 3D meshes which is kind of like a wireframe model and it can generate these from coarse to fine. You can stop'

[36:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this process at any time to get a valid mesh depending on how much detail you want. So as you can see here is one example of this generation of a cat. You can specify how many steps you wanted to'

[36:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'run this for. And of course the longer you run it the more details and edges it would add to this cat. Or here\'s another example. Now, in terms of 3D modeling, this is kind of like a trade-off between'

[36:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complexity and efficiency. So, the more like faces or edges you have for your model, then it\'s going to be more complex. It\'s going to take a longer time to load, but it\'s going to be more detailed. So, it depends what you\'re going after. Now, this vertex regen is'

[36:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'able to pull this off using a very smart technique. So vertex regen is actually an AI that was trained to reverse this process called edge collapse. This is basically a way to simplify a mesh by'

[36:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reducing the amount of edges in that model. So that\'s edge collapse, but vertex regen is basically trained to do the opposite. It\'s trained to add more edges, in other words, more details to a'

[37:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D model the more steps you run it. And so after training this AI, it\'s able to generate a mesh from coarse to fine with increasing level of detail depending on like how many steps you run this for.'

